Bug.WithStack:
I received the following code snippet as a suggested performance improvement.
This would also eliminate the "out of handles" seen using the IBM JRE due to
excessive jar_cache<id>.tmp files. 

When plugins leverage the compatibility runtime, jar_cache files are created. 
The is triggered by IPluginDescriptor.getResourceBundle().  This would also be
cause by Platform.getResourceBundle(bundle) provided the Plugin/Bundle has a
requirement for the compatibility runtime.

When the Bundle is treated as a 2.1 Plugin, a new ClassLoader is built to load
the plugin.properties.  The URLs added to the URLClassLoader are of the form
bundleentry://xx/yyyy and in most cases point to a JAR file, e.g.,
bundleentry://59/infra.jar.  These eventually get wrapped as a JAR URL so they
look like jar://bundleentry://59/infra.jar/!.  The request to find the resource
is delegated to each URL.  The URLClassLoader creates a "Loader" for each URL. 
If the URL is considered local, the file on disk is used directly otherwise a
local copy is made since the assumption is its remote.  The check looks
specifically for a file:// URL.

A solution is to resolve all URLs to a native URL using Platform.resolve. I
believe its something the Eclipse guys might just want.  

